1\" src=\"https://pressbooks.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/ebook-social-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"ebook image\" width=\"640\" height=\"427\" srcset=\"https://pressbooks.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/ebook-social-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https://pressbooks.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/ebook-social-300x200.jpg 300w, https://pressbooks.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/ebook-social-768x512.jpg 768w, https://pressbooks.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/ebook-social-1000x667.jpg 1000w, https://pressbooks.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/ebook-social-480x320.jpg 480w, https://pressbooks.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/ebook-social-65x43.jpg 65w, https://pressbooks.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/ebook-social-225x150.jpg 225w, https://pressbooks.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/ebook-social-350x233.jpg 350w, https://pressbooks.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/ebook-social.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" /></a></h2>\r\n<p>There are certain stylistic elements you can’t force when you’re formatting an ebook. What are some of these things and why is that the case? Here are a few examples of attributes it’s tough to control in ebooks: dropcaps, hanging indents, running headers, running footers and body fonts. Dropcaps in ebooks Dropcaps are one element that you can’t entirely control in ebooks.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://pressbooks.com/blog/ebook-formatting-answers-dropcaps-indents-headers-footers-and-fonts/\" rel=\"external nofollow\">Source</a></p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:28;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:36:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:53:\"Don’t Make These Rookie Self-Pub Marketing Mistakes\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"